1
00:01:54,414 --> 00:01:56,109
<i>I'm just a kid.</i>

2
00:01:56,549 --> 00:01:58,016
<i>There's a lot I don't know.</i>

3
00:01:59,586 --> 00:02:01,076
<i>But one thing I do know...</i>

4
00:02:01,221 --> 00:02:03,451
<i>is my folks never</i>
<i>should have married.</i>

5
00:02:03,957 --> 00:02:06,357
<i>And they definitely should've</i>
<i>never had a kid.</i>

6
00:02:08,695 --> 00:02:11,163
<i>But they did. That happens.</i>

7
00:02:11,598 --> 00:02:13,862
<i>The randomness of life</i>
<i>and all that.</i>

8
00:02:15,268 --> 00:02:18,431
When the chicken's up, I'm gonna
go out back and work on my boat.

9
00:02:19,739 --> 00:02:23,698
<i>Maybe they started out trying</i>
<i>to be good parents. I don't know.</i>

10
00:02:24,511 --> 00:02:26,911
<i>But my very first</i>
<i>memory in life is...</i>

11
00:02:27,213 --> 00:02:29,579
<i>how much my father</i>
<i>loved that damn boat.</i>

12
00:02:31,384 --> 00:02:35,047
<i>Here he is hundreds of miles</i>
<i>away from any real water.</i>

13
00:02:35,321 --> 00:02:37,915
<i>And even then we're talking</i>
<i>about the Gulf of Mexico.</i>

14
00:02:39,893 --> 00:02:41,827
<i>Just seemed sad to me, somehow.</i>

15
00:02:44,264 --> 00:02:48,064
<i>And my mom has been psychotically</i>
<i>obsessed with movie stars...</i>

16
00:02:48,201 --> 00:02:50,795
<i>to a point that</i>
<i>defies explanation.</i>

17
00:02:53,940 --> 00:02:55,407
I could use a bath.

18
00:02:58,545 --> 00:03:00,308
Well, go take a bath.

19
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:03,513
<i>Note that she was going</i>
<i>to take a bath...</i>

20
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:06,011
<i>the shower was</i>
<i>out of the question because...</i>

21
00:03:06,352 --> 00:03:09,082
<i>two years ago</i>
<i>some pipe in our shower broke.</i>

22
00:03:12,926 --> 00:03:14,518
<i>My father could've fixed it...</i>

23
00:03:14,827 --> 00:03:17,057
<i>but he was so tied up</i>
<i>working on the boat...</i>

24
00:03:17,163 --> 00:03:20,758
<i>he hired this</i>
<i>Marlon Brando plumber instead.</i>

25
00:03:26,539 --> 00:03:28,632
<i>And the shower never got fixed...</i>

26
00:03:28,741 --> 00:03:30,800
<i>as if it just</i>
<i>never happened.</i>

27
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:34,070
<i>Then there was</i>
<i>the Paul Newman thing...</i>

28
00:03:34,814 --> 00:03:36,873
<i>when our roof needed fixing.</i>

29
00:03:43,823 --> 00:03:45,154
<i>And, of course...</i>

30
00:03:45,258 --> 00:03:48,159
<i>our roofing problem</i>
<i>never got fixed, either.</i>

31
00:03:52,999 --> 00:03:55,934
<i>And how could I forget the day</i>
<i>Audrey Hepburn came over...</i>

32
00:03:56,069 --> 00:03:57,969
<i>to help my mom</i>
<i>with the books.</i>

33
00:04:00,139 --> 00:04:03,700
<i>On second thought, I'd really</i>
<i>rather not get into that one.</i>

34
00:04:06,112 --> 00:04:08,478
<i>It's not their fault,</i>
<i>if you think about it.</i>

35
00:04:09,215 --> 00:04:12,673
<i>It's not like they sat down</i>
<i>and had this conference about...</i>

36
00:04:12,785 --> 00:04:15,413
<i>whether they'd get married</i>
<i>and bear a son or not.</i>

37
00:04:17,056 --> 00:04:18,148
<i>Anyway...</i>

38
00:04:18,391 --> 00:04:22,088
<i>the story is that years ago</i>
<i>my father was a traveling salesman...</i>

39
00:04:22,195 --> 00:04:25,130
<i>that just happened to stop</i>
<i>on one Christmas Eve.</i>

40
00:04:31,504 --> 00:04:35,304
<i>My mother was engaged to the son</i>
<i>of a pharmacist over at Lubbock...</i>

41
00:04:35,708 --> 00:04:37,903
<i>and he chose the night</i>
<i>of the Christmas dance...</i>

42
00:04:38,011 --> 00:04:42,038
<i>to confess he'd fallen in love with</i>
<i>this cheerleader from Texas Tech.</i>

43
00:04:42,949 --> 00:04:45,383
I sure could use
a hot cup of coffee.

44
00:04:45,818 --> 00:04:47,410
I just made a fresh pot.

45
00:05:00,433 --> 00:05:02,594
<i>So, she was vulnerable</i>
<i>that night.</i>

46
00:05:03,069 --> 00:05:04,627
<i>You can't blame her for that.</i>

47
00:05:09,409 --> 00:05:11,377
That is some good,
good coffee!

48
00:05:12,111 --> 00:05:13,043
Thank you.

49
00:05:13,279 --> 00:05:15,406
And that's a handsome coat.

50
00:05:16,749 --> 00:05:19,377
To say nothing of your pretty dress,
which I love, by the way...

51
00:05:19,485 --> 00:05:21,316
because of the way
it matches your eyes.

52
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:24,248
Not exactly.

53
00:05:24,590 --> 00:05:27,218
Well, of course not exactly,
it'd be too obvious.

54
00:05:28,127 --> 00:05:31,221
We both know that's not
the kind of woman you are.

55
00:05:32,632 --> 00:05:36,932
<i>Was their meeting some fated day</i>
<i>that would magically find us...</i>

56
00:05:37,036 --> 00:05:39,971
<i>happy one day,</i>
<i>like a real family?</i>

57
00:05:40,940 --> 00:05:44,034
<i>No, it's not the way</i>
<i>things work.</i>

58
00:05:44,110 --> 00:05:45,839
<i>That much, I figured out.</i>

59
00:05:50,416 --> 00:05:54,785
<i>My mother had just come from seeing</i>
<i>"Splendor in the Grass", I think.</i>

60
00:05:55,688 --> 00:05:59,522
<i>She went to the movies every day,</i>
<i>and we only had one theater, so...</i>

61
00:05:59,859 --> 00:06:00,883
<i>whatever was playing.</i>

62
00:06:02,562 --> 00:06:03,927
<i>That's when it happened...</i>

63
00:06:04,797 --> 00:06:06,992
<i>and it changed my life forever.</i>

64
00:06:48,274 --> 00:06:49,901
Help me.
Better get her inside.

65
00:07:32,819 --> 00:07:34,719
Hospital says
it will be about a week...

66
00:07:34,787 --> 00:07:38,245
till we can get her down to Galvenston
where her grandparents live.

67
00:07:38,825 --> 00:07:41,385
We appreciate
you taking her in like this.

68
00:07:41,694 --> 00:07:43,787
- It's the right thing to do.
- Thank you, Mr. Reynolds.

69
00:07:45,331 --> 00:07:46,525
<i>It's strange.</i>

70
00:07:47,633 --> 00:07:50,625
<i>My folks can't remember</i>
<i>they're married half the time...</i>

71
00:07:51,237 --> 00:07:55,571
<i>and for them I'm just</i>
<i>a ghost flipping around the place.</i>

72
00:07:57,777 --> 00:08:00,405
<i>Then they go and agree</i>
<i>to take in this girl...</i>

73
00:08:00,746 --> 00:08:02,941
<i>whose parents died</i>
<i>in the accident...</i>

74
00:08:03,449 --> 00:08:04,677
<i>'till she got better.</i>

75
00:08:46,659 --> 00:08:48,092
Come in, please.

76
00:09:01,974 --> 00:09:03,271
Brought you stuff for dinner.

77
00:09:06,045 --> 00:09:08,980
Are you aware I have
a partially lacerated liver?

78
00:09:09,882 --> 00:09:13,909
Do you even have the slightest concept
of what that does to one's appetite?

79
00:09:15,922 --> 00:09:16,889
Not really.

80
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:23,521
My liver is
partially lacerated but...

81
00:09:24,597 --> 00:09:27,122
I don't have a clue
what it does to your appetite.

82
00:09:27,266 --> 00:09:29,097
It probably can't help.

83
00:09:31,737 --> 00:09:33,102
I'm not hungry.

84
00:09:37,109 --> 00:09:38,076
OK.

85
00:09:38,778 --> 00:09:41,008
I'll just leave it here for you.

86
00:09:48,387 --> 00:09:50,582
My parents' bodies were
sent back to Amarillo...

87
00:09:50,723 --> 00:09:52,247
for burial, I take it.

88
00:09:53,025 --> 00:09:55,994
How was the accidente listed
on the official police report?

89
00:09:57,163 --> 00:09:58,130
Speeding...

90
00:09:58,631 --> 00:10:00,565
driving while intoxicated?

91
00:10:02,969 --> 00:10:04,061
I'm not really sure.

92
00:10:06,906 --> 00:10:08,806
My father was a heavy drinker,
you know.

93
00:10:09,809 --> 00:10:10,776
No, I...

94
00:10:11,577 --> 00:10:12,703
didn't know that.

95
00:10:13,446 --> 00:10:15,175
Well, now you do.

96
00:10:17,316 --> 00:10:20,774
That was one goddamn accident,
that's for sure.

97
00:10:22,088 --> 00:10:23,055
What?

98
00:10:23,322 --> 00:10:25,381
You never heard
anyone cuss before?

99
00:10:25,591 --> 00:10:27,252
Well, yeah, but...

100
00:10:27,326 --> 00:10:28,691
not from a girl.

101
00:10:29,562 --> 00:10:31,120
Well, I'm very flawed.

102
00:10:32,765 --> 00:10:35,325
Extremely flawed,
if you want to know the truth.

103
00:10:46,912 --> 00:10:49,346
<i>I looked up the word</i>
<i>"flawed" in the dictionary.</i>

104
00:10:50,549 --> 00:10:54,485
<i>I kind of knew what it meant but,</i>
<i>after reading the definition...</i>

105
00:10:55,221 --> 00:10:58,588
<i>I began to wonder if</i>
<i>maybe I was flawed, too.</i>

106
00:11:00,559 --> 00:11:04,290
<i>But the strangest part was</i>
<i>that for the first time in my life...</i>

107
00:11:04,997 --> 00:11:09,093
<i>I started to feel something</i>
<i>for someone other than myself.</i>

108
00:11:10,670 --> 00:11:13,468
<i>It scared the hell out of me,</i>
<i>if you want to know the truth.</i>

109
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:16,034
<i>But I liked it.</i>

110
00:11:37,363 --> 00:11:38,523
You were screaming.

111
00:11:50,543 --> 00:11:51,510
It's late.

112
00:11:52,778 --> 00:11:54,177
You should go back to sleep.

113
00:12:16,035 --> 00:12:17,002
Jesus!

114
00:12:19,004 --> 00:12:20,767
You're not screwing
with me, are you?

115
00:12:21,173 --> 00:12:23,198
- What?
- You seem to like me...

116
00:12:23,342 --> 00:12:25,833
which is fine, because
I like you, too, but...

117
00:12:26,378 --> 00:12:28,471
if you're acting like you do
because my parents are dead...

118
00:12:28,581 --> 00:12:30,776
and you feel sorry for me,
then that's just bullshit.

119
00:12:34,286 --> 00:12:35,583
- Hello?
- No.

120
00:12:35,688 --> 00:12:38,987
I'm not screwing with you.
I like you, too.

121
00:12:39,091 --> 00:12:40,115
Good.

122
00:12:40,493 --> 00:12:42,586
I think it's time
for us to leave.

123
00:12:45,898 --> 00:12:46,990
Leave?

124
00:12:50,169 --> 00:12:53,332
Look, those two people
you live with...

125
00:12:53,572 --> 00:12:55,665
- they're nice and everything...
- My parents?

126
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:56,867
Right.

127
00:12:57,576 --> 00:12:58,975
But from what I can tell...

128
00:12:59,345 --> 00:13:01,540
they don't really have
anything to offer you...

129
00:13:01,747 --> 00:13:03,942
and they certainly
don't have a thing to offer me.

130
00:13:06,318 --> 00:13:08,718
So, where are we going?

131
00:13:09,155 --> 00:13:10,349
Baltimore.

132
00:13:11,390 --> 00:13:13,153
I have an aunt
and an uncle there.

133
00:13:13,492 --> 00:13:15,687
I haven't seen them
since I was five but...

134
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:19,288
from what I can remember,
they're extremely hip.

135
00:13:22,168 --> 00:13:24,363
But I thought when you got better
you were going to go...

136
00:13:25,070 --> 00:13:27,231
live with your grandparents
in Galvenston.

137
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:29,608
Look...

138
00:13:29,675 --> 00:13:30,607
Ben...

139
00:13:31,677 --> 00:13:35,545
there's what happens to you in life
and there's what you make happen.

140
00:13:35,915 --> 00:13:38,042
It's the difference
between having a plan and not.

141
00:13:39,118 --> 00:13:42,110
- Do you see what I'm driving at here?
- Yeah. I think so.

142
00:13:42,688 --> 00:13:43,655
Good.

143
00:13:46,592 --> 00:13:50,528
Well, I'm used to getting up
at the break of day...

144
00:13:50,796 --> 00:13:53,264
being all melodramatic
about this.

145
00:15:22,421 --> 00:15:23,752
How much did you get?

146
00:15:25,090 --> 00:15:26,352
25 bucks.

147
00:15:27,126 --> 00:15:29,959
Well, it's 25 more bucks
than we had before.

148
00:15:31,297 --> 00:15:32,389
That's true.

149
00:16:18,644 --> 00:16:22,603
See, a real plan is more
than just some pipe dream.

150
00:16:23,148 --> 00:16:24,137
Pipe dream?

151
00:16:25,050 --> 00:16:27,211
A pipe dream is
an unrealistic fantasy...

152
00:16:27,353 --> 00:16:30,288
that deludes oneself into thinking
that it's an actual plan.

153
00:16:31,156 --> 00:16:32,953
It's a very
popular expression.

154
00:16:33,258 --> 00:16:34,919
I'm surprised you've never
heard of it before.

155
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:36,693
I didn't say I never heard it.

156
00:16:36,795 --> 00:16:39,286
Anyway, a real plan
is an actual goal...

157
00:16:39,431 --> 00:16:43,128
that you believe in enough
to create a set of circumstances...

158
00:16:43,469 --> 00:16:46,666
which leads you to
and into a plan.

159
00:16:47,272 --> 00:16:50,139
- Do you understand?
- Where do you come with this stuff?

160
00:16:50,476 --> 00:16:54,344
I mean, what part of your brain
works so hard...

161
00:16:54,446 --> 00:16:56,380
that it makes you
think and talk like that?

162
00:16:56,515 --> 00:16:59,211
My father was a professor
with a very wide vocabulary...

163
00:16:59,318 --> 00:17:00,751
and lots of unique ideas.

164
00:17:01,353 --> 00:17:04,151
When he wasn't teaching
the students, he taught me.

165
00:17:04,556 --> 00:17:05,887
So, what did your mom do?

166
00:17:08,761 --> 00:17:10,353
She never did anything.

167
00:17:19,772 --> 00:17:20,739
You know...

168
00:17:20,806 --> 00:17:22,774
I think most
of what you say is true.

169
00:17:24,209 --> 00:17:26,541
Some I just don't understand.

170
00:17:26,979 --> 00:17:29,777
But I also think you like
to screw with people's heads.

171
00:17:33,018 --> 00:17:34,610
I may be wrong sometimes...

172
00:17:35,754 --> 00:17:37,722
but I won't ever
screw with your head.

173
00:17:38,524 --> 00:17:39,650
Ever.

174
00:17:40,692 --> 00:17:41,784
Me, too.

175
00:17:42,661 --> 00:17:43,650
Ever.

176
00:17:53,272 --> 00:17:55,604
Take a look at our
new home, farmboy.

177
00:17:56,809 --> 00:17:57,776
Here?

178
00:17:58,577 --> 00:17:59,976
See that pan over there?

179
00:18:00,779 --> 00:18:01,939
It's a hoghouse.

180
00:18:02,548 --> 00:18:05,108
Now, why would
a perfectly good hog...

181
00:18:05,584 --> 00:18:07,814
not be outside
on a day like this?

182
00:18:09,588 --> 00:18:12,250
So you're saying
they don't have any more hogs?

183
00:18:13,559 --> 00:18:15,993
I'm making
a calculated deduction.

184
00:18:21,033 --> 00:18:22,523
So, what's your plan?

185
00:18:24,503 --> 00:18:25,834
It's important.

186
00:18:26,071 --> 00:18:28,369
I need to know what kind of plan
you have for your life.

187
00:18:57,436 --> 00:19:00,928
My wife saw you
come in from across the road.

188
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:04,668
She made you these sandwiches.

189
00:19:07,279 --> 00:19:10,840
There's a well
by the gas tank if...

190
00:19:11,250 --> 00:19:12,239
you need water.

191
00:19:12,551 --> 00:19:14,178
How much do we owe you...

192
00:19:14,987 --> 00:19:16,921
for room,
and board and water?

193
00:19:21,326 --> 00:19:23,385
I imagine going to sleep...

194
00:19:25,397 --> 00:19:27,695
to the smell of pig shit
ought to do it.

195
00:19:41,046 --> 00:19:42,172
OK.

196
00:19:42,681 --> 00:19:45,149
I want to be a pitcher
for the St. Louis Cardinals.

197
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:50,754
So, you'll be a pitcher
for the Cardinals?

198
00:19:51,723 --> 00:19:52,712
I like that plan.

199
00:19:53,258 --> 00:19:57,126
Do you know how many kids my age
want to play in the Major Leagues?

200
00:19:57,362 --> 00:19:58,329
No.

201
00:19:58,397 --> 00:20:00,194
But I don't think it matters.

202
00:20:00,332 --> 00:20:04,962
I'm just saying it's more what you'll
call a pipe dream than an actual plan.

203
00:20:06,205 --> 00:20:07,229
Are you any good?

204
00:20:09,875 --> 00:20:11,672
I'm always the best
in my league.

205
00:20:12,311 --> 00:20:13,801
Is it what you really want to do?

206
00:20:16,982 --> 00:20:17,949
Yeah.

207
00:20:19,017 --> 00:20:19,949
Yeah.

208
00:20:20,018 --> 00:20:22,486
Then, it's not a pipe dream,
it's a plan.

209
00:20:22,988 --> 00:20:24,455
Learn to embrace it.

210
00:20:50,048 --> 00:20:51,072
Cassie?

211
00:20:53,719 --> 00:20:55,846
Did you know Joe Nuxhall is
the youngest guy ever...

212
00:20:55,887 --> 00:20:57,377
to play for the Major Leagues?

213
00:20:57,923 --> 00:20:58,912
Yeah.

214
00:20:59,124 --> 00:21:02,025
He started pitching for
the Cincinatti Reds at 15.

215
00:21:02,227 --> 00:21:05,754
This is correct. And more than once
you're gonna break his record.

216
00:21:18,977 --> 00:21:22,140
Try hitting the corners. You're putting
everything right down the middle.

217
00:21:22,514 --> 00:21:24,379
I'm not putting everything
right down the middle.

218
00:21:24,549 --> 00:21:27,450
Come on! It's the seventh game
of the World Series.

219
00:21:27,552 --> 00:21:28,951
Bottom of the ninth.

220
00:21:29,087 --> 00:21:30,645
Bases are full,
two out.

221
00:21:31,256 --> 00:21:34,817
You've got two strikes up.
One more strike and he's yours.

222
00:21:34,960 --> 00:21:38,487
And you know the only pitch you could
throw is the outside slider...

223
00:21:38,597 --> 00:21:41,293
because that's the only pitch
he won't be expecting.

224
00:21:44,436 --> 00:21:45,368
What?

225
00:21:46,071 --> 00:21:47,800
I don't know how to throw a slider.

226
00:21:49,308 --> 00:21:51,503
You kind of hold it off center...

227
00:21:52,077 --> 00:21:54,272
middle finger on the seam.

228
00:21:54,579 --> 00:21:56,376
Then you throw it
like a pass ball.

229
00:22:14,499 --> 00:22:15,761
Come on, giddy up!

230
00:22:16,301 --> 00:22:19,236
- We don't have all day.
- Coming! Coming!

231
00:22:42,627 --> 00:22:44,390
I think you should
tell me what's going on.

232
00:22:45,630 --> 00:22:48,326
It's not part of the plan.

233
00:22:49,801 --> 00:22:53,032
<i>I'm sick of this!</i>
<i>What do you think you're doing?</i>

234
