00:47:09,893 --> 00:47:13,522
I can't tell you how pleased I am
with the way things have gone so far.

489
00:47:21,205 --> 00:47:23,036
What's going on
with that arm, anyway?

490
00:47:23,607 --> 00:47:26,735
It's all right,
just a little swollen.

491
00:47:34,418 --> 00:47:35,976
Jesus, Cas!

492
00:47:42,192 --> 00:47:44,524
Why can't this wait until
we get to Baltimore?

493
00:47:47,297 --> 00:47:49,731
Because your arm
is about to fall off.

494
00:47:58,775 --> 00:48:00,174
The fracture's healed...

495
00:48:00,244 --> 00:48:03,475
there is some severe inflammation
around that cut, young lady.

496
00:48:03,614 --> 00:48:04,876
Here you are, daddy.

497
00:48:14,892 --> 00:48:17,326
Where exactly around here
do you two live?

498
00:48:19,162 --> 00:48:21,255
A few miles from town.

499
00:48:23,033 --> 00:48:25,695
Our father was laid off
in the paper mill so...

500
00:48:26,470 --> 00:48:28,301
money is a little tight
right now.

501
00:48:29,239 --> 00:48:30,263
What paper mill?

502
00:48:30,407 --> 00:48:33,274
You really are a good brother
to have brought her here.

503
00:48:34,177 --> 00:48:37,374
Well, she's
the only sister I have.

504
00:48:37,881 --> 00:48:40,873
And I wouldn't trade my brother
for all the silver in the world.

505
00:48:41,084 --> 00:48:42,847
Isn't that sweet, honey?

506
00:48:43,287 --> 00:48:45,687
It is absolutely adorable.

507
00:48:46,990 --> 00:48:50,790
I think that face's definitely
going to break some hearts one day.

508
00:48:50,928 --> 00:48:55,262
- How old do you think he is?
- My brother is 12 years old...

509
00:48:55,432 --> 00:49:00,199
and I'm very sorry your daughter can't
find boys her own age to play with.

510
00:49:04,074 --> 00:49:05,336
What's your father's name?

511
00:49:05,876 --> 00:49:08,276
Virgil. That's his first name.

512
00:49:08,478 --> 00:49:11,208
Yeah, Virgil Pappas.

513
00:49:11,548 --> 00:49:13,846
I don't know anybody
named Pappas.

514
00:49:13,951 --> 00:49:17,216
You know like we said,
we live quite a way from town.

515
00:49:20,891 --> 00:49:22,381
Call the sheriff, Maris.

516
00:49:22,759 --> 00:49:25,250
- There's just something not right here.
- I'll get it, daddy.

517
00:49:50,220 --> 00:49:51,209
OK, look...

518
00:49:51,621 --> 00:49:53,020
here is the truth.

519
00:49:53,757 --> 00:49:55,190
Our mother got arrested...

520
00:49:55,292 --> 00:49:57,886
for armed robbery
five days ago in Arizona.

521
00:49:58,996 --> 00:50:01,089
Our father left
when we were little...

522
00:50:01,231 --> 00:50:03,859
and they were going to put us
in different foster homes.

523
00:50:04,001 --> 00:50:04,968
Oh, my!

524
00:50:05,102 --> 00:50:07,229
We've been together
our whole life...

525
00:50:08,038 --> 00:50:10,905
so we just decided to stay
with our cousins up in Vermont.

526
00:50:11,141 --> 00:50:12,972
You better be
telling the truth, son.

527
00:50:13,076 --> 00:50:15,374
You've all just been
so amazingly kind...

528
00:50:15,979 --> 00:50:17,879
I could not lie
if I wanted to.

529
00:50:19,082 --> 00:50:22,051
Once we get to Vermont,
I'll send whatever we owe.

530
00:50:23,120 --> 00:50:24,382
Gratefully.

531
00:50:28,125 --> 00:50:29,558
You are absolutely incredible.

532
00:50:29,626 --> 00:50:32,459
I mean, seriously, it was like
watching "Hamlet" or something.

533
00:50:32,796 --> 00:50:35,390
Maybe you should be an actor
when your baseball career is over.

534
00:50:35,532 --> 00:50:37,295
I thought I was supposed
to be a great writer.

535
00:50:37,434 --> 00:50:39,595
Yeah, don't be an actor.

536
00:50:39,703 --> 00:50:41,637
It's a way too skittish life style.

537
00:50:41,738 --> 00:50:44,263
So, what can I get you
little chickens this morning?

538
00:50:44,408 --> 00:50:48,003
Some silver dollar pancakes
or some piggies in a blanket, I bet?

539
00:50:48,345 --> 00:50:49,505
Two coffees, both black.

540
00:50:54,084 --> 00:50:56,450
So, I watched these people
behind you walk in.

541
00:50:56,853 --> 00:50:59,151
They look like real softies.

542
00:50:59,523 --> 00:51:01,286
I bet we can
catch a ride from them.

543
00:51:47,370 --> 00:51:49,964
<i>Cas was right about</i>
<i>her aunt and uncle being hip.</i>

544
00:51:50,907 --> 00:51:52,431
<i>They seemed to me at least.</i>

545
00:51:52,742 --> 00:51:54,869
Lemonade? It's delicious.

546
00:51:55,011 --> 00:51:58,845
<i>I mean, they took us in out of the blue</i>
<i>without making a big deal out of it.</i>

547
00:52:00,217 --> 00:52:01,479
<i>I'd say that's pretty hip.</i>

548
00:52:01,618 --> 00:52:03,347
- Cheers!
- Cheers!

549
00:52:06,456 --> 00:52:09,391
Anything we need to go over?

550
00:52:11,094 --> 00:52:15,292
I think with children
there need to be some rules.

551
00:52:15,432 --> 00:52:16,421
Like what?

552
00:52:16,566 --> 00:52:18,898
The only one I can think of
is when they should go to bed.

553
00:52:20,070 --> 00:52:21,128
Midnight?

554
00:52:22,506 --> 00:52:23,837
Sounds fair to you guys?

555
00:52:25,108 --> 00:52:26,598
It seems reasonable.

556
00:52:26,710 --> 00:52:30,111
OK, wait, I mean, let's be realistic.
What about the weekends?

557
00:52:30,614 --> 00:52:31,603
Right.

558
00:52:31,781 --> 00:52:32,839
You know?

559
00:52:34,784 --> 00:52:35,773
Two?

560
00:52:35,886 --> 00:52:37,751
Who goes to bed at two?
Come on. Four.

561
00:52:37,821 --> 00:52:40,255
What do you say three?
Everybody OK with that?

562
00:52:40,724 --> 00:52:43,215
Very generous parameters, uncle.

563
00:52:43,660 --> 00:52:46,322
We won't abuse
the privilege, sir.

564
00:52:47,364 --> 00:52:50,265
I have a most beautiful room for you.
There's a parachute on the ceiling.

565
00:52:50,567 --> 00:52:52,262
It will be like you're in a palace.

566
00:52:52,536 --> 00:52:54,527
Does it have a single
or a double mattress?

567
00:52:54,938 --> 00:52:56,963
- It has a single.
- We'll need a double.

568
00:52:57,274 --> 00:53:01,301
With my leg stiffening up sometimes
and the two of us being married and all.

569
00:53:04,047 --> 00:53:04,979
You're married?

570
00:53:05,048 --> 00:53:07,312
That must be what kids call
going steady these days.

571
00:53:07,417 --> 00:53:09,578
Oh, no, we're actually married.

572
00:53:11,421 --> 00:53:12,410
Yeah, look.

573
00:53:14,691 --> 00:53:16,682
Was it a large wedding?

574
00:53:16,960 --> 00:53:19,087
Well, about 20 or 30 head of...

575
00:53:19,629 --> 00:53:22,689
mostly hogs and some sows.

576
00:53:23,233 --> 00:53:24,791
Oh, and pigs.

577
00:53:25,235 --> 00:53:27,965
Yes, there were several pigs
in attendance as well.

578
00:53:30,607 --> 00:53:34,099
Well, I guess we'll get you
a double mattress, then.

579
00:53:44,788 --> 00:53:45,846
Well...

580
00:53:47,090 --> 00:53:48,057
Look who's up.

581
00:53:48,625 --> 00:53:51,287
We've recently started
getting up early.

582
00:53:51,494 --> 00:53:53,223
It's a sign of discipline, I think.

583
00:53:53,897 --> 00:53:54,955
You may be right.

584
00:53:55,065 --> 00:53:57,329
Oh, and tell your wife
thanks for the coffee.

585
00:53:57,701 --> 00:53:59,259
It's very good.

586
00:54:01,104 --> 00:54:03,436
- I'll be sure to tell her.
- Oh, and uncle...

587
00:54:03,974 --> 00:54:07,307
is it all right if we paint a strike
zone on the side of the building?

588
00:54:07,677 --> 00:54:08,609
We'll pay for the paint.

589
00:54:09,279 --> 00:54:12,043
You mean,
like a baseball strike zone?

590
00:54:12,482 --> 00:54:16,111
Yes, my husband's going to be
a Major League pitcher.

591
00:54:22,125 --> 00:54:23,615
Well,
I don't see a problem with that.

592
00:54:24,060 --> 00:54:26,995
Terrific!
Well, have a wonderful day.

593
00:54:28,265 --> 00:54:29,425
You, too.

594
00:54:31,334 --> 00:54:32,631
Both of you.

595
00:54:36,740 --> 00:54:38,708
- <i>Don't be nervous.</i>
- <i>This is fun!</i>

596
00:54:39,009 --> 00:54:40,533
<i>Okay. Is that all right?</i>

597
00:54:40,910 --> 00:54:42,673
<i>You do wait</i>
<i>to hear if they can handle it.</i>

598
00:54:43,647 --> 00:54:44,739
<i>I'm nervous.</i>

599
00:54:46,583 --> 00:54:49,450
<i>Well, no more waiting.</i>
<i>I think I'm ready.</i>

600
00:54:50,253 --> 00:54:51,982
OK, the show is
about to start, sir...

601
00:54:52,122 --> 00:54:54,181
and your cooperation
is appreciated.

602
00:54:54,491 --> 00:54:56,721
Please remain in your seat or
I may have to call security.

603
00:54:57,260 --> 00:54:59,091
What are you guys up to, anyways?

604
00:54:59,296 --> 00:55:00,593
A pal direct from Paris...

605
00:55:00,730 --> 00:55:03,460
where she has been showing
for the kings and queens...

606
00:55:03,566 --> 00:55:05,864
and the very special
society's elite people...

607
00:55:06,002 --> 00:55:08,869
and the fashion world,
bright as a new star.

608
00:55:28,491 --> 00:55:29,480
Thank you.

609
00:55:32,529 --> 00:55:34,429
I'm so glad you had this dress on
and not the green shawl.

610
00:55:34,564 --> 00:55:36,327
Remember how the glare
had us hypnotized?

611
00:55:36,466 --> 00:55:38,832
I know, I remember.
I kept staring at it.

612
00:55:40,937 --> 00:55:42,268
The dream's glare...

613
00:55:54,217 --> 00:55:55,912
<i>At first, I couldn't really tell...</i>

614
00:55:56,853 --> 00:56:00,084
<i>but Cassie was starting</i>
<i>to slip away inside herself.</i>

615
00:56:24,881 --> 00:56:25,870
Thanks, man.

616
00:56:26,249 --> 00:56:27,341
Come on, Satchmo.

617
00:56:27,884 --> 00:56:30,717
- I can't do that.
- You played like hell the last time.

618
00:56:30,854 --> 00:56:33,118
I thought Armstrong
himself was in the room.

619
00:56:33,256 --> 00:56:34,723
Yeah, I got goosebumps.
Do it again.

620
00:56:34,824 --> 00:56:35,916
Come on, give it a try.

621
00:56:36,626 --> 00:56:37,650
All right.

622
00:56:38,328 --> 00:56:39,295
Take your time.

623
00:56:46,836 --> 00:56:49,430
<i>When I look back,</i>
<i>it feels like my fault.</i>

624
00:56:51,074 --> 00:56:53,838
<i>Not that I could've</i>
<i>figured out why she was sad...</i>

625
00:56:54,711 --> 00:56:58,875
<i>but not being able to see just</i>
<i>how incredibly sad she really was.</i>

626
00:57:02,719 --> 00:57:04,118
<i>The problem was...</i>

627
00:57:04,788 --> 00:57:06,983
<i>I didn't know</i>
<i>what to do about it.</i>

628
00:57:09,192 --> 00:57:10,124
Strike 3!

629
00:57:15,532 --> 00:57:16,658
Good job!

630
00:57:27,243 --> 00:57:29,677
<i>It's like she had</i>
<i>this grip on me...</i>

631
00:57:30,313 --> 00:57:32,873
<i>but was also pushing away</i>
<i>as hard as she could.</i>

632
00:57:34,017 --> 00:57:35,609
I can't find any frogs.

633
00:57:36,886 --> 00:57:38,683
I told you there weren't
going to be any here.

634
00:57:49,833 --> 00:57:50,765
It's funny?

635
00:57:53,169 --> 00:57:54,101
That's funny.

636
00:57:55,205 --> 00:57:58,231
Nice to see you got
some sense of humor left.

637
00:58:01,511 --> 00:58:02,500
How about a towel?

638
00:58:03,847 --> 00:58:04,973
There's a Summer League in Maine...

639
00:58:05,081 --> 00:58:07,106
where all
the Major League's touts go to.

640
00:58:07,584 --> 00:58:09,552
We're heading North
at the end of the week.

641
00:58:09,986 --> 00:58:11,476
If you don't sign in this year...

642
00:58:11,988 --> 00:58:14,684
we'll enrol you in school up there
and get you signed next summer.

643
00:58:14,824 --> 00:58:16,917
Cas, I'll be 13 next summer.

644
00:58:17,861 --> 00:58:20,091
Nobody signs 13-year-old kids.

645
00:58:21,931 --> 00:58:26,391
Sometimes your negativity
just absolutely exhausts me.

646
00:58:26,703 --> 00:58:28,898
What if I like it here
and don't want to leave?

647
00:58:29,038 --> 00:58:32,235
Going to Maine is the plan.
You want to screw it up?

648
00:58:32,575 --> 00:58:34,065
Go throw yourself a party.

649
00:58:36,679 --> 00:58:37,873
How about the towel?

650
00:58:48,958 --> 00:58:52,189
OK, what is the first name
of Ernest Hemingway's wife...

651
00:58:52,328 --> 00:58:54,728
the last one, when he blew
his brains all over the place?

652
00:58:58,668 --> 00:58:59,760
Duke.

653
00:59:00,403 --> 00:59:01,495
Mary.

654
00:59:02,572 --> 00:59:03,732
OK.

655
00:59:04,340 --> 00:59:07,935
Who is the right fielder
for the Cleveland Indians 1959?

656
00:59:09,979 --> 00:59:12,573
Sir Douglas big stick
or something.

657
00:59:14,517 --> 00:59:15,950
Rocky Colavito.

658
00:59:19,489 --> 00:59:20,649
Yes, my lord.

659
00:59:23,860 --> 00:59:27,193
You've almost completely
changed since we got here.

660
00:59:28,665 --> 00:59:31,065
I need to know what's going on.

661
00:59:32,569 --> 00:59:36,437
The real question is why you're
putting it in such a negative context.

662
00:59:36,839 --> 00:59:40,331
Yes, I am withdrawing somewhat,
but is that a sin?

663
00:59:42,779 --> 00:59:43,837
Great.

664
00:59:44,314 --> 00:59:48,273
Take a major problem, even though
you won't tell me what it is...

665
00:59:48,651 --> 00:59:52,212
and turn it into one
of your brainy discussions.

666
00:59:52,789 --> 00:59:55,121
Oh, is that your opinion?

667
00:59:55,525 --> 00:59:59,928
You did finish 7th grade, so I want
to give it the way it deserves.

668
01:00:00,530 --> 01:00:03,192
And you graduated
from Harvard, all right?

669
01:00:04,300 --> 01:00:06,825
OK, cowboy, you want to play?

670
01:00:08,972 --> 01:00:11,372
I'm not exactly sure about
what we're playing here, but...

671
01:00:12,208 --> 01:00:13,140
yeah, let's go.

672
01:00:14,077 --> 01:00:15,942
It's all about introspection...

673
01:00:16,145 --> 01:00:19,546
a concept you're no doubt incapable
of digesting at this point...

674
01:00:19,649 --> 01:00:22,345
in your narrow-minded,
sheltered, pathetic life.

675
01:00:26,723 --> 01:00:28,247
Go screw yourself!

676
01:00:44,507 --> 01:00:45,565
Ben...

677
01:00:47,076 --> 01:00:48,373
What?

678
01:00:50,079 --> 01:00:51,637
You mad at me?

679
01:00:53,883 --> 01:00:55,111
Yeah.

680
01:00:56,986 --> 01:00:58,749
And I don't like it.

681
01:01:00,923 --> 01:01:03,824
Then, start talking to me
like a real person.

682
01:01:08,965 --> 01:01:11,866
I told you I was flawed
when we met.

683
01:01:13,636 --> 01:01:14,864
Cas...

684
01:01:15,438 --> 01:01:19,340
Everybody's flawed.
Just in different ways.

685
01:01:25,682 --> 01:01:27,377
I'm so sorry.

686
01:01:32,255 --> 01:01:33,517
It's OK.

687
01:02:10,026 --> 01:02:11,288
Talk to me.

688
01:02:12,595 --> 01:02:13,789
Please.

689
01:02:33,349 --> 01:02:34,281
Oh, yeah!

690
01:03:01,778 --> 01:03:02,972
Ben, come on.

691
01:03:06,182 --> 01:03:07,274
You look good together.

692
01:03:17,593 --> 01:03:19,959
Hey, Cassie, honey.
Won't you come fun?

693
01:03:21,063 --> 01:03:21,995
Come here!

694
01:03:22,865 --> 01:03:23,797
Come on, Cassie.

695
01:03:24,267 --> 01:03:25,461
Let's show them how to do it.

696
01:03:28,404 --> 01:03:29,496
Come on, shake you tail.

697
01:03:35,044 --> 01:03:35,976
Good.

698
01:04:20,790 --> 01:04:22,917
<i>After a while,</i>
<i>Cassie calmed down...</i>

699
01:04:23,559 --> 01:04:24,958
<i>and went to sleep.</i>

700
01:04:26,262 --> 01:04:29,197
<i>I guess I hoped that</i>
<i>when she woke up...</i>

701
01:04:29,332 --> 01:04:30,890
<i>things would be OK.</i>

702
01:04:37,206 --> 01:04:38,571
<i>But I was wrong.</i>

703
01:05:48,978 --> 01:05:50,240
Time to go, honey.

704
01:06:29,385 --> 01:06:30,374
Come on!

705
01:06:34,457 --> 01:06:36,550
<i>So, Cassie became a patient...</i>

706
01:06:36,692 --> 01:06:39,354
<i>in a children's psychiatric ward</i>
<i>in Virginia.</i>

707
01:06:39,929 --> 01:06:40,953
Ready, front!

708
01:06:42,098 --> 01:06:44,828
<i>And I ended up that summer</i>
<i>in a bullshit Military Academy...</i>

709
01:06:44,967 --> 01:06:46,366
<i>down in North Carolina.</i>

710
01:06:47,436 --> 01:06:50,803
<i>Cassie's aunt and uncle figured</i>
<i>they had to do something with me...</i>

711
01:06:51,741 --> 01:06:54,574
<i>but listening to Louis Armstrong...</i>

712
01:06:54,977 --> 01:06:57,673
<i>and sending a boy</i>
<i>to a Military Academy...</i>

713
01:06:58,047 --> 01:07:00,106
<i>doesn't really chime,</i>
<i>when you think about it.</i>

714
01:07:00,182 --> 01:07:02,343
Reynolds, you're messed.
Tuck your shirt in!

715
01:07:03,386 --> 01:07:04,318
Fix your hat!

716
01:07:05,788 --> 01:07:07,688
Don't look at me,
look forward!

717
01:07:09,759 --> 01:07:11,283
Present arms!

718
01:07:12,361 --> 01:07:14,056
<i>The only reason I stuck around...</i>

719
01:07:14,397 --> 01:07:16,661
<i>was to see if Cassie</i>
<i>would get better or not.</i>

720
01:07:18,367 --> 01:07:19,629
<i>But she didn't.</i>

721
01:07:20,202 --> 01:07:22,227
<i>She'd gone over this edge...</i>

722
01:07:22,638 --> 01:07:24,230
<i>and nobody knew</i>
<i>how to get her back.</i>

723
01:07:24,373 --> 01:07:25,431
Maybe she will.

724
01:07:27,176 --> 01:07:29,076
<i>Then, the state made it official.</i>

725
01:07:29,945 --> 01:07:32,345
<i>Cassie would be put</i>
<i>in a high-risk observation...</i>

726
01:07:32,448 --> 01:07:35,246
<i>ward for a period</i>
<i>no less than 18 months.</i>

727
01:07:37,386 --> 01:07:38,512
<i>18 months.</i>

728
01:07:39,555 --> 01:07:40,954
<i>Unbelievable.</i>

729
01:07:41,290 --> 01:07:44,020
Reynolds,
I told you to grab some polish!

730
01:07:44,293 --> 01:07:45,317
Put that book down.

731
01:07:45,995 --> 01:07:46,984
I told you!

732
01:07:51,834 --> 01:07:54,735
<i>I know what to do</i>
<i>or where to go.</i>

733
01:07:56,272 --> 01:07:57,830
<i>I thought about back home.</i>

734
01:07:58,574 --> 01:08:02,101
<i>Maybe my folks had half the police</i>
<i>in Texas looking for me.</i>

735
01:08:05,081 --> 01:08:07,447
<i>But what did it all mean, really?</i>

736
01:08:08,784 --> 01:08:12,049
<i>They were living their lives,</i>
<i>and I, trying to figure out my own.</i>

737
01:08:13,055 --> 01:08:16,547
<i>The truth is, we never had</i>
<i>much in common, anyway.</i>

738
01:08:28,737 --> 01:08:29,761
Hot chocolate?

739
01:08:31,040 --> 01:08:32,029
Hot coffee.

740
01:08:37,880 --> 01:08:38,812
Thanks.

741
01:08:46,088 --> 01:08:47,146
You're a good kid.

742
01:08:48,124 --> 01:08:50,957
You should see mine, too.
Both boys.

743
01:08:51,694 --> 01:08:53,355
A little bit older than you,
but not much.

744
01:08:54,697 --> 01:08:58,565
Every day I look for even
the slightest sign of humanity in them.

745
01:09:00,302 --> 01:09:01,360
Not a drop.

746
01:09:04,073 --> 01:09:05,438
Where are you headed in Richmond?

747
01:09:07,276 --> 01:09:09,073
Children's psychiatric ward.

748
01:09:09,912 --> 01:09:11,641
I'm going there to get somebody out.

749
01:09:13,949 --> 01:09:17,146
Do the people running the hospital
know that you're coming?

750
01:09:17,853 --> 01:09:18,785
No.

751
01:09:22,858 --> 01:09:24,223
So you are...

752
01:09:25,094 --> 01:09:29,155
going to illegally take someone
out of the psychiatric ward?

753
01:09:30,032 --> 01:09:30,964
Yes, sir.

754
01:09:37,039 --> 01:09:38,097
Who are you bringing out?

755
01:09:39,575 --> 01:09:40,599
My wife.

756
01:09:43,546 --> 01:09:44,478
Your wife?

757
01:09:45,981 --> 01:09:47,846
Look, son...

758
01:09:50,452 --> 01:09:54,889
if you're the one who's staying
in the hospital, it's OK to tell me.

759
01:09:56,058 --> 01:09:58,390
No, I'm married...

760
01:09:59,895 --> 01:10:01,988
and I'll go get my wife out
and take her with me.

761
01:10:13,542 --> 01:10:14,474
Any kids?

762
01:10:15,878 --> 01:10:18,847
No, but planning
on having two eventually.

763
01:10:21,750 --> 01:10:24,412
I'll make it easy on both of you,
take mine.

764
01:10:39,301 --> 01:10:40,325
- Same ol'.
- Good night.

765
01:12:34,750 --> 01:12:35,808
Hey.

766
01:12:38,287 --> 01:12:39,447
Hey.

767
01:12:44,927 --> 01:12:46,258
Cas...

768
01:12:48,697 --> 01:12:49,629
Yeah.

769
01:12:52,901 --> 01:12:54,300
It's time to go.

770
01:13:00,175 --> 01:13:01,665
Is that the plan?

771
01:13:05,047 --> 01:13:06,173
Yeah.

772
01:13:07,383 --> 01:13:08,873
That's the plan.

773
01:13:11,220 --> 01:13:13,916
What if I'm really,
really tired?

774
01:14:31,333 --> 01:14:32,425
Let go! Let go! That's it!

775
01:14:45,047 --> 01:14:47,413
You took it for as long
as you could, Cas.

776
01:14:48,851 --> 01:14:50,716
You can't blame yourself for that.

777
01:14:56,992 --> 01:14:59,119
There were good parts to him, too.

778
01:15:05,868 --> 01:15:07,028
Cas...

779
01:15:08,437 --> 01:15:09,369
Yeah.

780
01:15:12,241 --> 01:15:13,367
Let's go.

781
01:15:17,679 --> 01:15:20,375
Ben, I'm sick.

782
01:15:22,184 --> 01:15:25,381
When you kill two people,
it makes you sick.

783
01:15:29,658 --> 01:15:33,094
Look, I'm going to take you
out of here and...

784
01:15:36,164 --> 01:15:37,961
worry about everything later. OK?

785
01:15:42,504 --> 01:15:43,528
OK.

786
01:15:54,750 --> 01:15:57,844
<i>Before Cas and I started</i>
<i>the rest of our lives together...</i>

787
01:15:58,353 --> 01:16:01,117
<i>there were a couple of things</i>
<i>I needed to do first.</i>

788
01:16:10,532 --> 01:16:14,366
<i>Sometimes it's hard knowing if</i>
<i>you should or shouldn't do something.</i>

789
01:16:19,274 --> 01:16:22,368
<i>So, you do what</i>
<i>feels right at the time.</i>

790
01:17:08,223 --> 01:17:09,622
My theater!

791
01:17:10,626 --> 01:17:11,786
My boat!

792
01:17:18,367 --> 01:17:19,334
My boat...

793
01:18:42,284 --> 01:18:44,752
<i>Who knows anything,</i>
<i>when it comes down to it?</i>

794
01:18:45,153 --> 01:18:46,381
<i>I don't.</i>

795
01:18:47,355 --> 01:18:50,449
<i>I pretend I do sometimes,</i>
<i>but I don't.</i>

796
01:18:56,198 --> 01:18:57,893
<i>But I do know this.</i>

797
01:18:58,366 --> 01:19:01,267
<i>When your life becomes</i>
<i>what you dreamed it would be...</i>

798
01:19:02,104 --> 01:19:03,264
<i>it's amazing.</i>

799
01:19:06,308 --> 01:19:09,766
<i>I think that walk sealed</i>
<i>D.Q.'s fate here in game five.</i>

800
01:19:18,320 --> 01:19:21,517
<i>I didn't break Nuxhall's record</i>
<i>of playing at 15...</i>

801
01:19:22,591 --> 01:19:26,322
<i>but I did become the youngest guy</i>
<i>that ever pitched in a World Series.</i>

802
01:19:26,428 --> 01:19:27,656
<i>Benjamin Reynolds.</i>

803
01:19:35,170 --> 01:19:36,660
<i>But nothing I did on the field...</i>

804
01:19:36,772 --> 01:19:39,639
<i>compared to what Cassie</i>
<i>and I accomplished together.</i>

805
01:19:45,013 --> 01:19:46,708
<i>It's kind of a miracle really...</i>

806
01:19:47,382 --> 01:19:50,078
<i>having the chance to give</i>
<i>what you never got.</i>

807
01:19:52,020 --> 01:19:54,580
<i>Cas took a job editing</i>
<i>children's books...</i>

808
01:19:55,457 --> 01:19:58,426
<i>and I pitched until my arm</i>
<i>couldn't take it any more.</i>

809
01:19:58,827 --> 01:20:00,795
<i>And, like she planned...</i>

810
01:20:01,263 --> 01:20:02,855
<i>I became a writer.</i>

811
01:20:06,935 --> 01:20:09,665
<i>A lot of what Cassie said</i>
<i>turned out to be true.</i>

812
01:20:10,472 --> 01:20:12,531
<i>Most people do need a plan.</i>

813
01:20:16,178 --> 01:20:18,476
<i>Life is crazy enough without one.</i>

814
01:20:26,888 --> 01:20:28,617
<i>But the hardest part of life...</i>

815
01:20:29,124 --> 01:20:31,115
<i>is losing someone you love.</i>

816
01:20:32,661 --> 01:20:35,824
<i>At first, you almost wish</i>
<i>you never knew them...</i>

817
01:20:36,097 --> 01:20:38,156
<i>so you stop hurting so much.</i>

818
01:20:38,900 --> 01:20:40,868
<i>Feels like it's going to kill you.</i>

819
01:20:57,752 --> 01:20:59,913
<i>What you end up missing the most...</i>

820
01:21:00,088 --> 01:21:02,579
<i>is the sweet burden</i>
<i>of being needed.</i>

821
01:21:03,625 --> 01:21:05,593
<i>It gives your life a purpose.</i>

822
01:21:05,894 --> 01:21:06,952
<i>It really does.</i>

823
01:21:08,230 --> 01:21:10,061
<i>And it makes you feel great.</i>

824
01:21:12,834 --> 01:21:14,927
<i>That's something else</i>
<i>Cassie told me.</i>

825
01:21:16,204 --> 01:21:18,104
<i>It is all a part of the plan.</i>

